{
  "title": "Principle 8 -  Scale always has a hard limit.",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f22801c7d548d7c7",
      "text": "There is a limit to the number of people and teams that can be added to an initiative to increase value delivery over time."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e74b1cb2277527a9",
      "text": "When the limit is reached, adding more people or teams will reduce the ability of the initiative to deliver—this is a consequence of Amdahl's Law ([[Gene M. Amdahl , 1967]]), stated also, in different terms, in [[Fred Brooks, 1995]].\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "0797609181cd6581",
      "text": "<img width=\"100%\" src=\"https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/51078579488_4dd161a47e_o.png\" />"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b0d5cc3d0a48a3f7",
      "text": "- The total time spent in sequential activities (anything that has to be done by one team at the time but affects most or all other teams, e.g., the creation of a common component or library, setting up some common infrastructure for testing and CI, etc.) is a lower bound for the time necessary to deliver the required functionality. The initiative cannot go faster than that."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4ec5e5c8ee51e5b2",
      "text": "- The maximum number of independent sub-initiatives, in which the main initiative can be split, is an upper bound to the maximum number of teams that can be added productively to the initiative. Note that “independent” in this context is a relative concept—sub-initiatives of a big initiative always have some dependencies among them, and “independent” ones have just a few."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "63386ef65bfcf142",
      "text": "- The “shape” of the system is a major constraint impacting the ability of the initiative to scale (Conway’s Law)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "14878f41f865b124",
      "text": "- The cost per feature increases more than linearly with the number of people and teams."
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
