      "text": "# Comments from Agile Cambridge 2022"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "98a0c2662dd4812b",
      "text": "What do limits reveal? What to evolve to push the limits?\nSome limits to scaling are embedded in the way we process relationships (e.g. 7 as a magic number for teams).\nConway’s law, getting the architecture wrong has a massive impact on team structure. The shape of the system is a major constraint.\nTotal time of sequential activities = initiative cannot go faster than that, so one has to remove the accidental causes/dependencies that make an activity sequential leaving only the essential causes.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3a5ceae529ad791f",
      "text": "There is the need to acknowledge that more teams or bigger teams don't mean faster. How to find and recognise the limit has been reached?\nCost per feature increases more than linearly with the number of people or teams.\nThe cost of communication exceeds the cost of doing the work. The large teams don’t work well\n The number of teams has increased to the point teams are not productive anymore.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "847fb87d4847c4e4",
      "text": "\"Sequential activities: how to balance the need for expertise for shared code with the waiting for it?\" A fundamental practice for knowledge sharing in Agile is transparency, shared ownership, and most of all pair/mob/ensemble programming or pairing in general where the knowledge sharing happens when doing the work and instead of being a const it is increase productivity.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "35be5fe7c271629a",
      "text": "\"Our brain likes patterns, scaling can be achieved with some rules around teams, team of teams, etc.\" We are not insects and such an approach does not work with human beings. As principle 7 at point e suggests, every circumstance may lead to different solutions that are fit for such circumstances.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "98f2501c1b8ff010",
      "text": "# Comments from SPA 2021\n\nThe size of a delivery initiative (scope and budget and so people), is one of the test predictors of a failure (the bigger, the less likely to succeed). See the Chaos Report from the Standish Group.\n  \nAn example of the people size predictor here is a story. Logica in the 1970s ran a project for a large bank. 130 people were beavering away for over a year to produce a functional specification and a data model. This Analysis Paralysis was resolved by a courageous project manager (Harry Webster RIP) who took 2 dozen people out of the team to do the actual work; the rest were kept busy doing nothing."
    }
